Depending upon the ways to connect tetrahedrally coordinated P-atoms in a 2D lattice, different structural allotropes can be formed. We have considered several allotropes of phosphorene, including $\beta$-P, $\gamma-\mathrm{P}, \delta-\mathrm{P}, \varepsilon-\mathrm{P}, \tau-\mathrm{P}, \eta-\mathrm{P}, \theta-\mathrm{P}, \phi-\mathrm{P}, \kappa_{4}-\mathrm{P}, \mathrm{R}-\mathrm{P}, \mathrm{O}-\mathrm{P}$ and $\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{P}$. All these allotropes are found to be semiconducting with calculated band gap varying from $0.48 \mathrm{eV}$ to $2.09$ eV (Table S1 of ESI). The magnitude of the relative formation energies (ERFmono) of all these $2 \mathrm{D}$ allotropes are found to be of the order of $10-10^{2} \mathrm{meV}$ /atom, indicating their ease of formation. This suggests that not only the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-P, but the other allotropes can also be experimentally realized. Hence, it is worth to explore the properties of other allotropes. Note that $\mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{RFm}}$.no can be obtained as: $E_{R F m o n o}=\frac{E_{A}-N E_{\alpha}}{N}$, where $E_{A}$ is the total energy of the considered phosphorene allotrope and $E_{\alpha}$ is the energy per atom of the most stable phosphorene allotrope i.e. $\alpha$-P and $N$ is the number of atoms per unit cell of the allotrope. Similarly, the cohesive energies are in the range of $-5.50$ to $-5.66$ eV/atom and are comparable to that of $\alpha-\mathrm{P}$ ( $-5.68$ eV/atom) (Table $\mathrm{S} 1$ of ESI).

Figure 1 shows the different types of possible edges of allotropes of phosphorene considered. Each allotrope cut along the distinct edges gives rise to a distinct phosphorene nanoribbon. The honeycomb structures ( $\alpha-\mathrm{P}, \beta-\mathrm{P}, \gamma-\mathrm{P}, \delta$-P and R-P) possess two edge structures one along $\mathrm{x}$-direction and the other along $\mathrm{y}$-direction. Unlike these honeycomb structures which possess only one type of edge along each direction, the non-honeycomb structures possess more than one different types of edges along different directions. Due to perfect square symmetry in the unit cell of $\varepsilon-\mathrm{P}$ and $\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{P}$, they possess two different edge structures $\left(\varepsilon_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \varepsilon_{\mathrm{x} 2}\right.$ and $\mathrm{O}_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \mathrm{O}_{\mathrm{x} 2}$ ) along one direction which are also similar in other direction (Figure 1). The $\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{P}$ allotrope also exhibit two types of edge structures $\left(\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{x} 1}\right.$ and $\left.\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{x} 2}\right)$ along one direction which are also similar in other direction due to the hexagonal symmetry in its structure. $\tau$-P forms four PNR structures corresponding to the two different type of edges along each direction shown in Figure 1. $\eta-P$ possesses 11 PNR structures, 5 along $\mathrm{x}$ axis $\left(\eta_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \eta_{\mathrm{x} 2}, \eta_{\mathrm{x} 3}, \eta_{\mathrm{x} 4}\right.$ and $\left.\eta_{\mathrm{x} 5}\right)$ and 6 along $\mathrm{y}$ axis $\left(\eta_{\mathrm{y} 1}, \eta_{\mathrm{y} 2}, \eta_{\mathrm{y} 3}, \eta_{\mathrm{y} 4}, \eta_{\mathrm{y} 5}\right.$ and $\left.\eta_{\mathrm{y} 6}\right)$ (Figure 1 \& Figure $\mathrm{S} 1$ of ESI). $\theta$-P possesses 7 PNRs structures, 4 along $\mathrm{x}$ axis $\left(\theta_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \theta_{\mathrm{x} 2}, \theta_{\mathrm{x} 3}\right.$ and $\left.\theta_{\mathrm{x} 4}\right)$ and 3 along $\mathrm{y}$ axis $\left(\theta_{\mathrm{y} 1}, \theta_{\mathrm{y} 2}\right.$ and $\left.\theta_{\mathrm{y} 3}\right)$. $\phi$-P form 6 PNR structures, 3 along $\mathrm{x}$ axis $\left(\phi_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \phi_{\mathrm{x} 2}\right.$, and $\left.\phi_{\mathrm{x} 3}\right)$ and 3 along $\mathrm{y}$ axis $\left(\phi_{\mathrm{y} 1}, \phi_{\mathrm{y} 2}\right.$ and $\left.\phi_{\mathrm{y} 3}\right) \cdot \kappa_{4}-\mathrm{P}$ possesses two different structures one along each direction $\left(\kappa_{4 \times 1}\right.$ and $\left.\kappa_{4 y 1}\right)$. The width of considered PNRs lies in the range $17 \AA$ to $46 \AA$ [Table 1].

