\subsection{Electronic and Carrier Transport Properties}
Next, we calculate the electronic structure of the PNRs considered. The semiconducting behavior of given PNRs varies from narrow-gap semiconductor $\left(\mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{g}}<1 \mathrm{eV}\right)$ to wide-gap semiconductor $\left(\mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{g}}>1 \mathrm{eV}\right)$. Passivation of edges with hydrogen increases the band gap of PNRs which lies in the range 0.3-2.2 $\mathrm{eV}$ [Table 1 and Figures 4]. The increase in bandgap on the edge-passivation is attributed to the pairing of electrons due to hydrogen atoms which

