The carrier mobility of most of the PNRs considered are found to be comparable with the monolayer black phosphorene (i.e. $10^{3} \mathrm{~cm}^{2} \mathrm{~V}^{-1} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$ ) with the exception of $\beta$-PNR, $\tau$-PNR, RPNR, and H-PNR. Particularly, the electron mobility of $\theta$-PNR and the hole mobility of $\varepsilon$-PNR is found to be one order higher than $\alpha$-PNR [Figure 5 and Table S1of ESI]. The electron mobility of the passivated PNRs including $\alpha_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \varepsilon_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \eta_{\mathrm{y} 2}, \theta_{\mathrm{y} 3}, \phi_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \phi_{\mathrm{y} 3}, \kappa_{4 \mathrm{x} 1}, \mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{y} 1}, \mathrm{O}_{\mathrm{x} 2}, \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{x} 1}$ is higher than their hole mobility indicating their n-type semiconducting characteristic whereas $\beta_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \gamma_{\mathrm{x} 1}$, $\delta_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \tau_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \tau_{\mathrm{y} 2}, \eta_{\mathrm{x} 3}, \theta_{\mathrm{x} 1}$ behaves like p-type semiconductors owing to their higher hole mobility. Among the PNRs considered, $\alpha_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \delta_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \varepsilon_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \tau_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \tau_{\mathrm{y} 2}, \eta_{\mathrm{x} 3}, \theta_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \phi_{\mathrm{x} 1}, \phi_{\mathrm{y} 3}, \kappa_{4 \mathrm{x} 1}$ and $\mathrm{O}_{\mathrm{x} 2}$ PNR changes their carrier mobility, thereby, the semiconducting character (n-type $\leftrightarrow$ p-type) after the passivation of the edges with $\mathrm{H}$-atoms. Our results indicate that the intrinsic band gap and high carrier mobility possessed by these PNRs may find various applications in nano- and optoelectronics.

\section{Summary}
In summary, stability, electronic and mechanical properties of nanoribbons of 13 phosphorene allotropes namely $\alpha-\mathrm{P}, \beta-\mathrm{P}, \gamma-\mathrm{P}, \delta-\mathrm{P}, \varepsilon-\mathrm{P}, \tau-\mathrm{P}, \eta-\mathrm{P}, \theta-\mathrm{P}, \phi-\mathrm{P}, \kappa_{4}-\mathrm{P}, \mathrm{R}-\mathrm{P}, \mathrm{O}-\mathrm{P}, \mathrm{H}-\mathrm{P}$ have been investigated. The magnitude of formation energies of PNRs considered is found to be comparable to their monolayer counterparts indicating their ease of formation. Deformation potential theory within the effective mass approximation have been employed to the most stable semiconducting bare and passivated PNRs to analyse their carrier transport properties. On passivation of edges, band gap increases along with direct $\leftrightarrow$ indirect transition in some cases. The effective mass of most of the PNRs is less than $0.3 \mathrm{~m}_{\mathrm{e}}$. The carrier mobility of most of the PNRs is found to be comparable to that of the monolayer $\alpha$-P. The unique features of the PNRs considered render them as favourable $1 \mathrm{D}$ materials to be used in applications relating to phosphorene based devices.

